ble_remove()`. These are the exact loops the commit message says the new refcount was supposed to replace -- only the one in `forward_close()` at `:2046` got converted. Dup-heavy workloads still pay the pre-patch cost on those paths.\n\n   Fix: replace each loop with `kbox_fd_table_lkl_ref_count(ctx->fd_table, shadow_lkl) == 0` after the `remove()` call, mirroring the pattern already used in `forward_close()`.\n\n3. Direct negative-sentinel writes to `entry->host_fd` bypass `rev_host_clear()`. At `src/seccomp-dispatch.c:1174` and `:1617` the lazy-shadow promotion paths assign `KBOX_FD_LOCAL_ONLY_SHADOW` / `KBOX_FD_HOST_SAME_FD_SHADOW` directly. If the entry previously held a positive `host_fd`, the reverse map still points at `vfd` after the write. The forward-check in `find_by_host_fd` keeps lookups correct (the mismatch on `e->host_fd == host_fd` rejects the stale hit), but when the host kernel later recycles that fd number and a new owner calls `set_host_fd`, `rev_host_set` sees a non-matching prior value and immediately poisons the slot to `MULTI` -- compounding issue 1.\n\n   Fix: call `rev_host_clear(t, entry->host_fd, vfd)` before writing the negative sentinel. Or expose a `kbox_fd_table_set_host_fd_sentinel()` helper and require callers to use it.\n\n## Validation notes\n\n- `lkl_ref_inc` saturates at `UINT16_MAX`, but this is unreachable: the maximum refs a single `lkl_fd` can have is bounded by `KBOX_FD_TABLE_CAPACITY = KBOX_FD_TABLE_MAX + KBOX_LOW_FD_MAX + KBOX_MID_FD_MAX = 36864`, comfortably below 65535. The narrower type is fine.\n- `insert_at`-over-live-slot: correct. `lkl_ref_dec` + `rev_host_clear` happen before `init_live_entry`, so no double-count and no stale reverse-map entry. This path also fixed a latent refcount leak the pre-patch code had.\n- Out-of-range guards on `rev_host_set` / `rev_host_clear` / `lkl_ref_inc` / `lkl_ref_dec` are correct; the linear-scan fallback in `kbox_fd_table_lkl_ref_count` is reachable when `lkl_fd >= KBOX_LKL_FD_REFMAX`.\n\n## Test suite gaps (extends @ChuWeiChang's plan)\n\nWhat 000015c added (`tests/unit/test-fd-table.c`) is only correctness:\n\n- `test_fd_table_find_by_host_fd_duplicate_holder_survives` -- MULTI sentinel + scan-order tie-break\n- `test_fd_table_find_by_host_fd_requires_api` -- direct `entry->host_fd` writes are intentionally not findable\n\nGaps to close before this can be marked done:\n\n1. Refcount lifecycle. Add unit tests that walk the full state machine -- `insert`, `set_host_fd`, `insert_at` over a live slot (the latent leak path that 000015c fixed), `remove`, and `close_cloexec_entry` -- and assert `kbox_fd_table_lkl_ref_count(lkl_fd)` at every step. The refcount is now load-bearing for `forward_close()`'s shadow-socket path; an off-by-one here will silently leak LKL FDs and we will not notice from integration tests.\n\n2. MULTI downgrade regression test. Once the sticky-MULTI fix lands, add a test that drives a host_fd through `single -> MULTI -> single` (via two `set_host_fd` calls then one `rev_host_clear`) and asserts `host_to_vfd[h]` returns to a non-sentinel `vfd`. Without this, the fix can silently regress and only show up as a perf cliff.\n\n3. O(1) characteristic test. Measure lookup cost as a function of table occupancy and assert it stays flat. Suggested shape: populate the table to N in {64, 256, 1024, 4096, 16384}, time M lookups of a known-present host_fd and a known-absent host_fd (the authoritative-NONE fast path), and assert the per-lookup cost ratio between the largest and smallest N stays under a generous bound (e.g. 2x) to absorb cache and noise. Run only in release builds -- ASAN will skew the numbers. A skip-on-debug guard plus a `KBOX_PERF_TESTS=1` gate keeps `make check-unit` deterministic on CI while still letting the bench gate run on arm.\n\n4. Reverse-map / `entries[]` consistency fuzzer. Drive `insert` / `insert_at` / `set_host_fd` / `remove` / `close_cloexec_entry` with a randomized op stream against a shadow oracle and assert (a) every `find_by_host_fd(h)` agrees with the oracle, (b) `lkl_fd_refs[k]` equals the oracle's count for every k, and (c) on teardown both the reverse map and the refcount array are all-zero / all-NONE. This is the cheapest way to catch the next latent leak before it ships.\n\n5. `forward_sendfile()` coverage. Sendfile's host-FD resolution rides the same `find_by_host_fd()` and gets the speedup for free, but we have no integration test that exercises a shadow `in_fd` through sendfile after the refactor. Add one to `tests/guest/` so the path is not dead in CI.\n\nConsolidation suggestion: items 1, 2, and 4 belong together in `test-fd-table-refcount.c` (or as an extension of `test-fd-table.c`) so the invariants are checked in one place. Item 3 should live behind the perf gate, not in `make check-unit`. Item 5 is a one-off integration test, separate file under `tests/guest/`.\n\nClosing once the three code gaps and the five test gaps above are in.\nEOF\n)\"",
