close` pair, all of it in the wrapper-level overhead. Correctness is gated to static binaries with no fork-family sites.\n\nWhat stage 2 did (the big one): replaced the 35.47 %-of-CPU linear `kbox_fd_table_find_by_host_fd` scan. Was walking all 36864 fd-table slots on every close just to discover that bench-test's cached-shadow open path never populates the table. New reverse map gives O(1) authoritative-miss via a `host_to_vfd[65536]` flat array. Eliminated 75 us of per-close overhead — all of it — and matched the TODO.md 47.3 us baseline within noise.\n\nWhat stage 3 did: the user added an O(n) repair scan to `rev_host_clear` to handle dup2-style duplicate holders correctly. This was correctness-safe but ran on every close and fully undid the stage-2 win. 4 → 119 us, back to baseline.\n\nWhat stage 4 did: replaced the repair scan with a third map state (`MULTI = -2`) that marks duplicate-holder slots. Close-path clears become O(1) again, duplicate scenarios stay correct by falling through to the slow scan only for the specific host_fd values that ever had duplicates. Bench-test recovers to 47.02 us.\n\nWhat stage 5 did: pure refactor. Extracted six copies of 6-field init/clear boilerplate into `clear_fd_entry` and `init_live_entry` helpers. Zero behavioral change. 47.02 → 47.07 us (within noise).\n\n## Profile shift\n\nBefore (pre-optimization):\n```\n35.47 %  kbox_fd_table_find_by_host_fd    ← linear scan per close\n 7.79 %  _raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore       (futex wake in service thread)\n```\n\nAfter (stage 5, final):\n```\n13.40 %  _raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore       ← new top, kernel futex wake\n 0.00 %  kbox_fd_table_find_by_host_fd    ← completely off the chart\n```\n\nThe 35 % linear-scan hotspot is gone. The new top hitter is the kernel's wake-up path for the supervisor service thread — orthogonal signaling cost, not dispatch work. That is the next optimization target if someone wants to keep pushing, but it is outside the scope of this round.\n\n## Secondary refactors, no perf impact\n\n- `lkl_fd_is_sole_ref` replaced the O(n) `lkl_fd_has_other_ref` scan with an O(1) refcount lookup (`kbox_fd_table_lkl_ref_count`). Relevant to `close_cloexec_entry` and `forward_close`'s shadow-socket handling. Not on bench-test's hot path but removes a latent O(n) cost.\n- `forward_close` still-ref inline scan in `src/seccomp-dispatch.c` replaced with `kbox_fd_table_lkl_ref_count() == 0`. Also not on bench-test's hot path but eliminates a second O(n) per-close scan.\n- `kbox_fd_table_insert_at` now releases the previous lkl_fd refcount and old reverse-map entry when reusing a live slot. This fixed a latent refcount leak I introduced in an earlier iteration.\n\n## What did not move\n\n`stat`, `lseek+read`, `write`, `getpid` are unchanged. Their hot paths are already near-native in rewrite mode (SVC trampoline on a direct-dispatch eligible wrapper). They were never bottlenecked by the FD-table scan because they operate on an already-open fd and take the fast fd→lkl_fd lookup, not the host_fd→vfd reverse path. No reason to expect any of the three optimizations in this round to move them, and none did.\n\n## Memory cost\n\n`struct kbox_fd_table` grew from ~1.13 MB to ~1.43 MB (+288 KB: 256 KB for `host_to_vfd[65536]` + 32 KB for `lkl_fd_refs[16384]`). Stack-allocated in the supervisor launch paths; default 8 MB Linux stack has plenty of headroom.\n\n## Summary\n\n**−75.9 µs per `open+close` pair. 2.61× faster. All tests still passing on lima. Nothing committed.**\n\nThe dominant win (~97 % of the total) came from replacing the linear reverse-FD scan with the O(1) hybrid reverse map. The cancel-wrapper fast path contributes a small (~3 us) additional improvement. Both are independently correct and testable. The simplifier's refactor keeps the code readable at no cost.",
