            "new_string": "# Changelog\n\n## 2026-04-08: aarch64 rewrite-mode open+close 2.59x faster\n\nCommits: `000050c`, `000015c` (branch `cancel-wrapper`, PR #51)\n\n### Completed slices moved out of `TODO.md`\n\n- **cancel-wrapper (`__syscall_cancel`) fast-path correctness** (from\n  P5 \"Syscall rewriting remaining work\"). Detect `bl __syscall_cancel`\n  at the libc wrapper level on aarch64 and redirect it to a dedicated\n  cancel trampoline entry that consumes the syscall number from `x6`\n  (matching musl's `__syscall_cancel(a,b,c,d,e,f,nr)` calling\n  convention) and resumes at `bl_pc + 4`. Site detection requires\n  `movz x6, #nr` followed by a `bl` within 32 bytes whose target is\n  validated by walking the call chain up to depth 2 looking for a\n  `svc #0` preceded by four or more consecutive `mov Xd, Xm`\n  arg-shuffle instructions, a signature specific to musl's\n  `__syscall_cancel_arch`. Promotion is gated on two independent\n  conditions: `launch->interp_elf == NULL` (static binary, so libc is\n  embedded in `main_elf` and `pthread_create`'s clone wrapper is\n  visible to the scanner) AND no fork/clone/vfork/clone3 wrapper sites\n  in `main_elf`. The fork-sites scanner previously returned 0 for all\n  aarch64 input; rewrote it to delegate through\n  `kbox_rewrite_has_wrapper_syscalls`, which handles both architectures\n  uniformly. Design note at `docs/cancel-wrapper.md`.\n\n- **Reverse-map host FDs to avoid O(n) close-path scans** (issue #38,\n  from P4 \"Enhancements\"). Profiling showed\n  `kbox_fd_table_find_by_host_fd()` consuming 35.47 % of total CPU on\n  the `bench_test open+close` loop: every `close()` of a tracee-held\n  host FD walked all 36864 slots (1024 low_fds + 31744 mid_fds + 4096\n  entries) linearly before returning -1, because the cached-shadow\n  `openat` path injects an ADDFD without ever creating an fd_table\n  entry. Added two flat tables:\n  - `host_to_vfd[65536]`: three-state reverse map\n    (`NONE`/`MULTI`/single-holder vfd) giving O(1)\n    `find_by_host_fd` on the authoritative-NONE path. The `MULTI`\n    sentinel preserves correctness for dup2/dup3-style duplicate\n    holders without any scanning on the common path.\n  - `lkl_fd_refs[16384]`: O(1) refcount replacing the\n    `lkl_fd_has_other_ref` scan and the `still_ref` loop inside\n    `forward_close()`'s shadow-socket teardown.\n  Maintained on every mutation point (`insert`, `insert_fast`,\n  `insert_at`, `set_host_fd`, `remove`, `close_cloexec_entry`).\n  `insert_at` now also releases the previous refcount and reverse-map\n  entry when reusing a live slot (latent refcount leak fix). Six\n  copies of 6-field slot-init boilerplate collapsed into two helpers,\n  `clear_fd_entry` and `init_live_entry`. Memory cost: struct\n  `kbox_fd_table` grows from ~1.13 MB to ~1.43 MB (+288 KB), stack\n  allocated in the supervisor launch paths. Out-of-range host_fds\n  (>= 65536) and lkl_fds (>= 16384) fall through to the original\n  linear-scan implementations as a safety net.\n\n### Performance\n\nReal aarch64 hardware (release build, `bench_test 10000` iterations,\nmean of 5 runs):\n\n| syscall    | baseline | + cancel-wrap | + fd-table O(1) |\n|------------|----------|---------------|-----------------|\n| stat       |   3.5    |     3.5       |     3.3 (noise) |\n| open+close | 122.97   |   119.76      |    **47.52**    |\n| lseek+read |  42.9    |    42.5       |    43.4 (noise) |\n| write      |   1.4    |     1.4       |     1.4         |\n| getpid     |   0.0    |     0.0       |     0.0         |\n\nNet `open+close` improvement: **−75.45 us / −61.4 % / 2.59x faster**.\nThe cancel-wrapper fast path contributes ~3 us of wrapper-level\noverhead removal; the fd-table O(1) rework contributes the remaining\n~72 us of per-close scan elimination. All other syscalls are\nunchanged.\n\n`perf record` confirms `kbox_fd_table_find_by_host_fd` is completely\noff the top chart after these changes; the new hotspot is\nkernel-side `_raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore` from futex wake-up in the\nsupervisor service thread (13.40 %), which is an orthogonal\nsignaling cost and a separate optimization target.\n\n### Tests\n\n- 273/273 unit tests pass on lima (aarch64, ASAN+UBSAN debug build),\n  including new coverage for the BL target validator, the arch-aware\n  fork scanner on aarch64, updated cancel-wrapper ELF expectations,\n  and two new fd-table tests documenting the hybrid-semantics\n  duplicate-holder and API-only invariants.\n- 51/51 integration tests pass on lima.\n- `bench_test`, `clone3-test`, `dup-test`, and `/bin/ls` all work\n  correctly on arm under `--syscall-mode=rewrite`. Static-binary\n  gate re-verified: `/bin/ls` (dynamic) reports\n  `cancel_promote_allowed=0`, `bench_test` (static) reports\n  `cancel_promote_allowed=1`.\n\n### Known residual limitations (tracked separately)\n\n- A static program that invokes `clone`/`clone3` via `syscall(3)`\n  (register-indirect `mov x8, x_reg; svc 0`) slips past the\n  wrapper-number scanner, which only matches the literal-immediate\n  pattern. The static-binary gate would approve such a binary even\n  though it can actually create threads. No test binary in the tree\n  exercises this pattern today. Pre-existing scanner limitation.\n- The shared-libc musl `__syscall_cancel` calling convention\n  differs from the static one (nr in `x0` vs `x6`). The current\n  BL-site detector only recognizes static-musl.\n\n## 2026-04-05: File bind mount support",
