itelist a precise instruction range rather than trying to identify \"kbox code\" some other way.\n\n### Issues\n\n**HIGH-1: `run_trap_launch` does not call `kbox_lkl_start_kernel`** (`image.c:237-299`)\n\nThe trap launch path builds `ctx` with `ctx.host_root = NULL` and never initializes LKL. But `kbox_dispatch_request` will call LKL functions (openat, stat, etc.) for every intercepted syscall. Either LKL must be initialized before the transfer, or the trap path needs a different dispatch strategy. As written, the first intercepted `open(\"/etc/passwd\")` will call `lkl_sys_openat()` on an uninitialized kernel and crash.\n\nThis may be intentional (trap mode only works for host-only syscalls right now), but if so it needs a comment and a guard in dispatch.\n\n**MED-1: `active_trap_runtime` global still lacks memory ordering** (`syscall-trap.c:15`)\n\nUnchanged from prior review. The signal handler reads this pointer. On aarch64, a store from the main thread may not be visible to the signal handler without a release/acquire barrier. In practice, `sigaction()` likely provides a full barrier on most kernels, but the C standard doesn't guarantee it.\n\n**MED-2: `pread_full` triplicated** -- now in `src/elf.c:70`, `src/rewrite.c:504`, and conceptually in the loader files. Three copies of the same 15-line function.\n\n**MED-3: BPF IP range requires `start >> 32 == (end-1) >> 32`** (`seccomp-bpf.c:313`)\n\nThe `emit_ip_range_allow` and `emit_ip_range_trap_match` functions reject ranges that cross a 4 GB boundary. For typical userspace mappings this is fine, but the constraint is undocumented and could silently fail if a guest binary is mapped near a 4 GB boundary. Should either document this or split such ranges.\n\n**MED-4: Redundant NULL guard in `origin_map_build_elf`** (`rewrite.c:909`) -- unchanged from prior review.\n\n**LOW-1: Missing loader files in git** -- `mk/features.mk` references `loader-entry.c`, `loader-handoff.c`, `loader-image.c`, `loader-layout.c`, `loader-stack.c`, `loader-launch.c` (via `run_trap_launch`). These plus `loader-transfer.c` exist as untracked files but aren't staged. Clean checkout will fail to build.\n\n**LOW-2: `align_up_u64` name collision** -- still exists between `elf.c` (returns int, overflow-checked) and `rewrite.c` (returns uint64_t, returns 0 on overflow).\n\n**LOW-3: `kbox_loader_transfer_to_guest` inline asm register constraints** (`loader-transfer.c:57-62`)\n\nThe x86_64 path loads registers `rdi`, `rsi`, `rdx`, `r10`, `r8`, `r9` from `state->regs[]` but uses them as input constraints to an asm block that overwrites `rsp` and jumps away. The compiler could theoretically reorder the register loads relative to the `mov rsp` since the asm block only has `\"memory\"` as a clobber. In practice, the `\"r\"` input constraints force the compiler to have all values in registers before the asm block executes, so this should be safe. But `\"cc\"` should be in the clobber list for completeness.\n\n### What's clean\n\n- The asm host syscall trampoline with labeled start/end symbols is the correct pattern for BPF IP whitelisting. Same approach used by gVisor and other seccomp-based sandboxes.\n- The BPF jump backpatching in `kbox_install_seccomp_trap_ranges` is correct -- I traced through the instruction offsets manually.\n- `rt_sigreturn` in the allow list is correct and necessary for trap mode.\n- The loader transfer to guest (`mov rsp; jmp *pc` / `mov sp; br x16`) is clean and matches how the kernel's ELF loader works.\n- `kbox_loader_transfer_to_guest` is correctly marked `__attribute__((noreturn))`.\n- The supervisor context in `run_trap_launch` correctly sets `guest_mem_ops = &kbox_current_guest_mem_ops` (in-process memory access, not `process_vm_readv`).\n- 47/47 integration tests pass (seccomp path unaffected).\n- Test coverage for new code is good (loader tests exist for all 7 loader modules).\n\n### Verdict\n\nSolid incremental progress. The trap mode path is now wired end-to-end for the first time: SIGSYS handler -> request decode -> dispatch -> result writeback, with BPF IP-range filtering to avoid trapping the supervisor's own syscalls. HIGH-1 (no LKL init in trap path) is the only blocker for actual trap-mode execution of guest binaries that touch the virtual filesystem. LOW-1 (unstaged loader files) will break clean builds.",
