          "text": "OK, I've now reviewed the complete updated changeset end-to-end. Here's the final validation.\n\n---\n\n## Validation Report: `syscall-rewriting` branch (rev 3)\n\n### Delta from rev 2\n\n+81 lines, all in `src/image.c` and `src/rewrite.c`:\n\n1. **`rewrite_requested` now includes AUTO**: `KBOX_SYSCALL_MODE_REWRITE || KBOX_SYSCALL_MODE_AUTO` -- AUTO mode now performs ELF rewrite analysis.\n\n2. **`run_rewrite_launch`** (`image.c:311-369`) -- new launch path that installs `kbox_rewrite_runtime` (live binary patching) + SIGSYS trap runtime as fallback, then transfers to guest.\n\n3. **AUTO mode cascade** (`image.c:756-840`): rewrite (if probe feasible) -> trap -> seccomp fallback. Three-tier selection logic.\n\n4. **`kbox_rewrite_runtime_install`** (`rewrite.c:1439-1544`) -- the real engine: collects planned sites from both main and interp ELFs with load bias applied, makes exec mappings writable, installs page-zero trampoline (x86_64) or per-slot aarch64 trampolines, patches syscall instructions in-place, restores protections, flushes icache.\n\n5. **x86_64 rewrite entry trampoline** (`rewrite.c:116-141`) -- `call *%rax` lands in page-zero -> `movabs $entry, %r11; jmp *%r11` -> `kbox_syscall_rewrite_x86_64_entry` which saves registers, calls `kbox_syscall_rewrite_x86_64_dispatch(origin_addr, nr, args_array)`, restores registers, returns to instruction after the original `syscall`.\n\n6. **aarch64 rewrite entry trampoline** (`rewrite.c:70-107`) -- `B trampoline` -> per-slot stub loads origin_addr into x17, entry into x16, `BR x16` -> `kbox_syscall_rewrite_aarch64_entry` which saves registers, calls C dispatch, restores, returns via `BR x16` to origin+4.\n\n7. **`init_launch_ctx`** extracted from `run_trap_launch` to eliminate duplication.\n\n### Architecture assessment\n\n```\n[Taste] Good\n[Critical Flaw] see HIGH-1\n[Fix] HIGH-1 is a correctness issue in the x86_64 rewrite entry stub\n```\n\n### Issues\n\n**HIGH-1: x86_64 `kbox_syscall_rewrite_x86_64_entry` uses wrong return mechanism**\n\nThe x86_64 entry stub at line 119-141:\n```asm\nmov (%rsp), %r11        # save return address\nsub $56, %rsp           # alloc args array\n... save regs ...\ncall kbox_syscall_rewrite_x86_64_dispatch\n... restore regs ...\nadd $56, %rsp\nret\n```\n\nThe `call *%rax` patch (0xff 0xd0) replaces a 2-byte `syscall`. On x86_64, `call *%rax` pushes the return address (address of instruction *after* the call, i.e. the byte that was *after* `syscall`) onto the stack, then jumps to `%rax`. The page-zero trampoline jumps to `kbox_syscall_rewrite_x86_64_entry`. The entry stub loads `(%rsp)` into `%r11` (the return address = original IP after syscall), does its work, then `ret` which pops the same return address and jumps back. This is correct -- the guest resumes at the instruction after the original `syscall` site. Good.\n\nWait -- but `%rax` contains the syscall number (not the trampoline address) when `call *%rax` executes. The patched bytes are `0xff 0xd0` which is `call *%rax`. If `rax = __NR_read = 0`, that calls address 0x0 which IS the page-zero trampoline. If `rax = __NR_write = 1`, that calls address 0x1, which is inside the NOP sled. If `rax = __NR_open = 2`, calls 0x2. The NOP sled (64KB of 0x90) slides to the tail which does `movabs entry, %r11; jmp *%r11`. So all syscall numbers 0..~65500 land somewhere in the NOP sled and slide to the entry. This is clever and correct.\n\nBut wait -- `sysenter` (0x0f 0x34) was also being patched to `call *%rax`. `sysenter` has different register conventions than `syscall` -- EAX is the syscall number but args are in different registers (EBX, ECX, EDX, ESI, EDI, EBP for 32-bit). Since kbox is 64-bit only and sysenter in 64-bit mode is deprecated/unusual, this is a minor concern. The entry stub assumes `syscall` ABI (RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9). If the guest somehow uses `sysenter` in 64-bit mode with the syscall ABI, it works. If not, args will be wrong. Document or skip sysenter patching.\n\n**HIGH-2: `ctx.host_root = NULL` in launch paths** (`image.c:251`)\n\nBoth `run_trap_launch` and `run_rewrite_launch` set `ctx.host_root = NULL` via `init_launch_ctx`. The seccomp path sets `host_root` to the LKL mount point. With `host_root = NULL`, path translation in `translate_guest_path` will break -- `kbox_translate_path_for_lkl` needs a non-NULL `host_root` to resolve guest paths to LKL filesystem paths. Same issue as HIGH-1 from rev 2: the trap/rewrite paths don't initialize LKL.\n\nThis means the trap and rewrite launch paths can only work for syscalls that don't touch the virtual filesystem (i.e., CONTINUE-only workloads). This may be the intended scope for this PR, but it's a hard crash on the first `open(\"/etc/passwd\")` and needs either a guard or documentation.\n\n**MED-1: `active_rewrite_runtime` global without atomics** (`rewrite.c:57`)\n\nSame pattern as the `active_trap_runtime` issue. Written in main thread, read in rewrite dispatch (which is the inline call from guest code, same thread). Since rewrite mode runs in-process single-threaded, this is actually safe -- no signal handler race here. The write happens before the guest starts executing. Downgrade from prior review.\n\n**MED-2: `pread_full` now in three files** -- `elf.c`, `rewrite.c`, and potentially loader files.\n\n**MED-3: aarch64 trampoline slot is written while mapping is PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC** (`rewrite.c:1516-1521`)\n\nThe trampoline address is inside the guest's exec mapping (past the end of the segment's file-backed data but within `mem_size`). `make_exec_mappings_writable` adds PROT_WRITE to exec pages, the trampoline is written, then protections are restored. But between write and icache flush, there's a window where another thread could execute stale icache. Single-threaded, so not a practical issue.\n\n**LOW-1: Missing loader files in git** -- still not staged. Build will fail on clean checkout.\n\n**LOW-2: x86_64 page-zero trampoline requires `vm.mmap_min_addr = 0`** -- correctly probed and reported, but the rewrite path in AUTO mode (`image.c:780`) gates on `exec_probe.feasible`, so if `mmap_min_addr != 0` on x86_64, AUTO falls through to trap. Correct behavior.\n\n**LOW-3: `write_le64` defined in rewrite.c but not in elf.c** -- elf.c uses `set_le64` in tests and `read_le64` in code. Naming inconsistency between files.\n\n### What's new and clean\n\n- The x86_64 NOP-sled page-zero trampoline is an elegant solution: `call *%rax` with any syscall number in RAX lands somewhere in a 64KB NOP sled that slides to the entry stub. No per-site trampoline needed. One page, all sites covered.\n- The aarch64 per-slot trampoline design (B instruction -> 32-byte slot with LDR literal + BR) handles the 128MB branch range limitation correctly. Slots are placed just past the segment's mem_size, within the page-aligned mapping.\n- `kbox_rewrite_runtime_install` has proper cleanup: `writable` flag tracks whether exec pages need protection restoration, `goto out` handles all error paths, `runtime_site_array_reset` frees collected sites.\n- Origin map validation in dispatch (`kbox_rewrite_origin_map_contains`) prevents arbitrary code from reaching the dispatch function -- only patched sites are accepted.\n- icache flush via `__builtin___clear_cache` after patching and before protection restoration is correct for aarch64.\n- The AUTO cascade (rewrite -> trap -> seccomp) with clear verbose logging at each decision point is good for debuggability.\n- 47/47 integration tests still pass (seccomp path unaffected by all changes).\n\n### Verdict\n\nThe rewrite runtime is now complete end-to-end for the first time. The architecture is sound: patch syscall instructions -> trampoline -> C dispatch -> host syscall or LKL emulation -> return to guest. HIGH-2 (no LKL in trap/rewrite paths) is the practical blocker -- these paths work for CONTINUE-only syscalls but will crash on any LKL-routed syscall. LOW-1 (unstaged loader files) remains a build blocker for cle