 LKL close. Shadow creation dominates.\n- lseek+read (25.7us): two notifs. Baseline predicts 25us (2x12.5),\n  but back-to-back notifications in a tight loop run faster than\n  standalone getpid due to hot kernel caches (seccomp filter, notif\n  path). Each call is a single LKL call; read copies 64B in one chunk.\n- write (27.1us): 12.5us notif + ~15us for process_vm_readv (64B buf) +\n  LKL write + optional TTY mirror. Single chunk (64B << 128KB).\n- getpid (12.5us): pure seccomp round-trip, returns hardcoded PID 1.\n\n~4.5 host context switches per intercepted syscall (weighted average).\n\nOverhead decomposition: seccomp notification vs LKL execution\n(measured on node1, median of 10 runs, seccomp notification floor =\n12.6us from getpid):\n\n| Syscall | kbox | notif cost | LKL+copy | notif share |\n|---------|------|-----------|----------|-------------|\n| stat | 17.6us | 12.6us (1x) | 2.8us | 82% |\n| open+close | 63.3us | 25.2us (2x) | 35.2us | 42% |\n| lseek+read | 26.4us | 25.2us (2x) | 0.2us | 99% |\n| write | 26.4us | 12.6us (1x) | 12.7us | 50% |\n| getpid | 12.6us | 12.6us (1x) | ~0us | 100% |\n\nThe seccomp notification round-trip dominates most syscalls: 82-100%\nfor stat, lseek+read, and getpid. Exceptions are open+close (58%\nLKL+shadow creation) and write (50% LKL + process_vm_readv copy).\nlseek+read is almost entirely notification overhead -- back-to-back\nnotifs in a tight loop hit hot kernel caches, so actual LKL work\n(lseek is a pointer reset, read copies 64B) is negligible.",
